The paper discusses a framework for optimizing media experiences on the web, which involves creating abstract page models and transforming them into real experiences through algorithmic experimentation. This involves retrieving dynamic content from multiple sources, defining degrees of freedom, and constraining algorithmic choices. The paper touches on several areas of computer science, including human-computer interaction (cs.HC), information retrieval (cs.IR), multimedia (cs.MM), social and information networks (cs.SI), and computation and language (cs.CL). However, given the focus on media experiences and optimization, we believe that cs.HC and cs.IR are the most likely categories, followed by cs.MM, cs.SI, and cs.CL.
